For {= person =}+ distinct people, find a page (i.e. {= url =}+ URL) showing each person currently works at Airbnb in a full-stack web engineering role with hands-on experience in technologies that overlap Perplexity's product-engineering stack — the goal is people who could plausibly contribute as Perplexity product engineers today.

The test is page-substantiveness, not page-source. Any surface works as long as the page itself carries enough material to verify all three claims (current Airbnb employment, full-stack web role-scope, and named-project-tied technology evidence). Substantive primary surfaces are most natural — a maintained engineer profile with bio context plus pinned repos showing the stack; a personal site detailing Airbnb work; an authored byline on an engineering publication; a conference talk speaker page; a substantive professional profile that exposes Education + Experience + named-project bullets; a substantive employer-hosted team / engineering page if it carries the same depth per individual. Sparse stub profiles, contact-data-aggregator scrapes, job-listing aggregators, and "best engineers at company X" listicles fail not because of where they live but because their content is too thin to substantiate the claims.

Requirements:
- The page must show Airbnb (or "Airbnb, Inc.") as the person's current primary employer — unambiguously-current present-tense framing (e.g. "@airbnb" in a maintained GitHub bio, a personal-site bio claiming current employment, or a Present / no-end-date Experience entry naming Airbnb). People whose Airbnb tenure has ended and who now work elsewhere do NOT count, even when the page mentions Airbnb prominently in a past-tense / "previously" framing.
- The page must show the person works as a full-stack web engineer — their visible work covers BOTH frontend (browser-side / web UI code) AND backend (services / APIs / databases) layers, **each tied to specific work on the page**. Must surface evidence of BOTH layers tied to actual work: a TS/JS/React pinned-repo title (with primary language), or "frontend"/"UI" in a project description, or a full-stack role label, AND a Python/Go/Rust/Ruby/Node pinned-repo title (with primary language), or "backend"/"services"/"API" in a project description, or "full-stack"/"web slinger" as an explicit bio role label, etc. A bare skills-keyword listing (e.g. "Staff Engineer | Ruby on Rails, EmberJS, React, PostgreSQL") without more concrete evidence tying technologies to shipped work does NOT establish the layer signals.
- The page ought to show hands-on shipping experience overlapping Perplexity's product-engineering stack — modern TypeScript and/or React on the web side AND at least one backend language Perplexity uses (Python, Go, Rust, or Node-on-TypeScript). Closely-related modern web technologies also count (Next.js, FastAPI, GraphQL, Redis, PostgreSQL, Docker, AWS) when paired with the core overlap signal. A JVM-only backend (Java / Kotlin / Scala / Spring) without any Python/Go/Rust/Node visible doesn't count, nor does a non-React-only frontend (Angular / Vue / Svelte / Ember) without React. Preact (React-API-compatible) counts as React-equivalent. The bar for "hands-on shipping" — and the realistic middle case for most pages — is that each named technology must be tied to a specific project, role-bullet, shipped artifact on the page, or similar, not merely listed as a keyword.